summary.p: 57 fol. on parchment; Shelfmark: Cod. Arab. 38; Qurʾānic text: Q 21:18-21:40, Q 21:43-22:63; 6 lines per page.
The Catalogue of Arabic Manuscripts of the Royal Library by Irmeli Perho describes this manuscript as follows (Perho 2007, pp. 93f.):

“Description: The fols. have been bound together. Traces of the spine remain holding the fols together. No covers. A loose front leaf and a loose end leaf, paper. Text fols. are parchment. No title page. Text begins on fol. 1a. Text in Kūfī script, black ink, red, black and green diacritics and vowel marks. Golden verse markers, every tenth verse marked with a golden circle with verse number. On fol. 28b, the title of the sūrah in gold within a golden panel, a golden medallion in the margin. On some fols. the text is rather faded. On fols. 10, 18, 19, 41, 43, and 53-56, the ink has etched through the parchment. Text ends on fol. 56b. Notes: The ms. consists of two fragments: fragment I: fols. Ia-7b; from verse 21:18, words ز]هق ولكم الويل] to verse 21:40, words ولا هم ينطرو[ن] fragment II: fols. 8a-56b; from verse 21:43, word يصحبون to verse 22:63, words الارض مخضرةا [ن] . The ms. described in Adler (1780), 22 and as number 6 in Lindberg (1830), 62-64. Owner's marks: On fol. Ia, in the lower right corner pencilled mark: "No. 3". On fol. 26b, in top margin, partly cut away: "Friderici A Bockwoldes." Provenance: The pencilled number (No 3) on fol. Ia is an old Royal Library Catalogue number (cf. Lindberg 1830, 62 and 1851-catalogue, entry XXXVIII). About the acquisition history, see entry Cod. Arab. 36 and Introduction."

Seven kufic Qur'an fragments owned by Friedrich Buchwald (1605-1676), who had acquired them on a journey, came to Denmark in the 18th century and, as the monogram in the binding shows, were added to the royal library in Copenhagen at the time of King Christian VII (1766-1808) (see Perho 2007 in the introduction and the entry Cod. Arab. 36). The seven fragments, accessible under the shelfmarks Cod. Arab. 36, Cod. Arab. 37, Cod. Arab. 38, Cod. Arab. 39, Cod. Arab. 40, Cod. Arab. 41 and Cod. Arab. 42 form the object of the first palaeographical study of Arabic script in the West: Driven by an interest in biblical textual criticism, the theologian and orientalist Jakob Georg Christian Adler (1756-1834) wrote his Descriptio codicum quorundam cuficorum partes corani exhibentium in bibliotheca regia hafniensi et ex iisdem de scriptura cufica arabum (Adler 1780), the first palaeographical treatise on Qur'an manuscripts, on the kufic fragments. It contains information on the history of Arabic script, illustrations and comparisons between the Arabic text contained in the fragments and the reference edition of the Arabic Qur'an text at the time, which Abraham Hinckelmann had printed in Hamburg in 1694 (Hinckelmann 1694).
